SIMPLE: loot
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Loot
<hw>Loot</hw> <pr>(l⟦oomac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Hind.
<ets>l⟦umac⟧⟦tsdot⟧</ets>, Skr. <ets>l⟦omac⟧tra</ets>,
<ets>l⟦omac⟧ptra</ets>, booty, <ets>lup</ets> to break, spoil; prob.
akin to E. <ets>rob</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
plundering.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Plunder; booty; especially, the booty taken in a
conquered or sacked city.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>Anything stolen or obtained
by dishonesty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <specif>Broadly:</specif> <def>Valuable objects; <as>as,
the child was delighted with all the <ex>loot</ex> he got for his
birthday</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Money; <as>as, you shouldn't carry all that
<ex>loot</ex> around with you in the city; she made a pile of
<ex>loot</ex> from trading in cattle futures</as>.</def>
<mark>[slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Loot</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Loot
<hw>Loot</hw>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Looted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Looting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To plunder; to carry off as
plunder or a prize lawfully obtained by war.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Looting</qex> parties . . . ransacking the houses.</q>
<rj><qau>L. Oliphant.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>looted</ent>⟦br⟧
